  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 34, 35.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And looking up to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "heaven,  he sighed, and saith unto him, Ephphatha, that is, Be opened",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". He looked up to heaven, because from thence come all good things - words for the dumb, hearing for the deaf, healing for all infirmities; and thus he would teach the infirm man by a manifest sign to what quarter he was to look for the true source of his cure. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "he sighed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐστέναξε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "he groaned.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Why did our Lord sigh at such a moment? We know indeed that he was \"a man of sorrows, and acquainted with grief;\" but now we might almost have expected a momentary smile of loving joy when he was about to give back to this afflicted man the use of these valuable instruments of thought and action. But he sighed even then; for he was touched with the feeling of human infirmity, and no doubt his comprehensive eye would take in the vast amount of misery, both bodily and spiritual, which has come upon the world through sin; and this, too, immediately after having looked up to heaven, and thought of the realm of bliss which for a time he had left \"for us men, and for our salvation.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Ephphatha",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "that is",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Be opened.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This word is, of course, addressed to the man himself; and the evangelist has retained the original Syro-Chaldaic word, as he has retained \"Talitha cumi\" elsewhere: so that the actual word which passed through the Saviour's lips, and restored speech and hearing to the afflicted, might be handed on, as doubtless it will be, to the end of time. The word applies of course, primarily, though not exclusively, to the ear; for not only were his ears opened; but the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "bond of his tongue was loosed, and he spake plain.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Mark 7:34",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
